---
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";
import { Leaf, History, TrendingUp, ArrowDown } from "lucide-react";
---

<section
    id="research-intro"
    data-chapter="research-intro"
    data-nav-label="Chapter 0: The Story"
    class="h-screen w-full flex items-center justify-center p-8 snap-start bg-muted/30 relative"
>
    <div class="container max-w-4xl text-center space-y-8">
        <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight lg:text-6xl text-gradient">
            Once Upon a Time, on Reddit...
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            They say the internet is a chaotic place. We say it’s a <span
                class="text-primary font-semibold">mirror</span
            >.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            <span class="font-semibold text-foreground"
                >Welcome to our data story!</span
            > We are the <span class="font-semibold text-foreground">Ambassadors for Data Appreciation Team</span>, and we’ve spent months analyzing
            the <span class="font-semibold text-foreground"><a href="https://snap.stanford.edu/data/soc-RedditHyperlinks.html">Reddit Hyperlink Network</a></span> dataset, a massive web of connections between distinct
            communities on everyone's favorite social media platform. Our mission? Prove that online discourse isn't random; it
            follows the heartbeat of the physical world.
        </p>

        <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
            In the chapters ahead, you won't just see graphs. You will see the <span
                class="font-semibold text-foreground"
                >rhythm of the seasons</span
            > affecting our collective mood, watch <span
                class="font-semibold text-foreground">real-world history</span
            > get reconstructed by anomaly detection algorithms, and (since, as everyone knows, money is everything) discover relationships between the <span
                class="font-semibold text-foreground"
                >stock market
            </span> and <span class="font-semibold text-foreground">Reddit anxiety</span>.
        </p>

        <div class="pt-8">
            <a href="#research-questions">
                <Button variant="outline" size="lg" className="gap-2">
                    Our Research Questions <ArrowDown className="h-4 w-4" />
                </Button>
            </a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section
    id="research-questions"
    data-subchapter="research-questions"
    data-nav-label="Research Questions"
    class="min-h-screen w-full flex items-center justify-center p-8 snap-start bg-background relative overflow-hidden"
>
    <div class="container max-w-7xl flex flex-col gap-12 justify-center h-full">
        <div class="text-center space-y-6">
            <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold lg:text-5xl">
                Key Research Questions
            </h3>
            <p class="text-xl text-muted-foreground max-w-2xl mx-auto">
                To navigate a dataset of this magnitude, we needed a compass.
                Our main question is: <br />
                <span class="font-semibold text-foreground italic">"Can we see an impact of real-world events on Reddit posts?"</span>
            </p>
        </div>

        {}
        <div class="w-full space-y-8 max-w-5xl mx-auto">
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 w-full text-left">
                {}
                <div
                    class="group p-6 rounded-2xl border border-border/60 bg-card transition-all duration-300 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md hover:border-blue-500/50 dark:hover:border-blue-400/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2 text-foreground">
                        Seasonal Variations
                    </h3>
                    <p class="font-medium text-foreground mb-2">
                        "How do emotions vary over the seasons and months of the year?"
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                        We investigate whether the 'Winter Blues' or the 'Summer
                        Joy' are just myths or measurable phenomena. By tracking
                        specific emotional markers during time, we discover 
                        the seasonal heartbeat hidden within piles of
                        comments.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {}
                <div
                    class="group p-6 rounded-2xl border border-border/60 bg-card transition-all duration-300 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md hover:border-green-500/50 dark:hover:border-green-400/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2 text-foreground">
                        Market Sentiment
                    </h3>
                    <p class="font-medium text-foreground mb-2">
                        "Is the stock market trend related to Reddit sentiment?"
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                        Can you predict sentiments of subreddits based on stock market trends of the related companies? 
                        We analyze the correlation
                        between erratic subreddit behavior and stock volatility
                        to see if Wall Street dances to the same tune
                        as Reddit.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {}
                <div
                    class="group p-6 rounded-2xl border border-border/60 bg-card transition-all duration-300 shadow-sm hover:shadow-md hover:border-orange-500/50 dark:hover:border-orange-400/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-2 text-foreground">
                        Predictive Power
                    </h3>
                    <p class="font-medium text-foreground mb-2">
                        "Can we leverage ML to predict Reddit sentiment based on real-world data?"
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                        We explore if machine learning can effectively predict
                        different aspects of Reddit sentiment using real-world
                        data signals, reconstructing the timeline of history
                        purely from the 'noise' of community interactions.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="flex justify-center pt-8">
            <a href="#seasonal-intro">
                <Button size="lg" className="gap-2">
                    Let's Start the Journey! <ArrowDown className="h-4 w-4" />
                </Button>
            </a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>
